# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: piezoelectric-actuators
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] An **inchworm motor** is a cooperative linear actuator system in which multiple elements (originally piezoelectric, later often electrostatic) are activated in a coordinated sequence of step-wise motions, enabling extended motion range relative to individual actuators and high-precision positioning.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Inchworm motors originated in the 1960s as multi-actuator mechanisms for high-precision positioning.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Driven by advances in micromachining and microfabrication, designs shifted in the 1990s toward electrostatic microactuators, employing coordinated step sequences to achieve precise, linear motion beyond the limits of single actuator elements.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] In its simplest form, the inchworm motor uses three piezo-actuators (2 and 3, see Figure 1.) mounted inside a tube (1) and electrified in sequence to grip a shaft (4) which is then moved in a linear direction.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Motion of the shaft is due to the extension of the lateral piezo (2) pushing on two clutching piezos (3).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] The actuation process of the inchworm motor is a six-step cyclical process after the initial relaxation and initialization phase.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Initially, all three piezos are relaxed and unextended.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Electrification of the piezo actuators is accomplished by applying a high bias voltage to the actuators in step according to the "Six Step" process described above.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] To move long distances the sequence of six steps is repeated many times in rapid succession.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Once the motor has moved sufficiently close to the desired final position, the motor may be switched to an optional fine positioning mode.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] In this mode, the clutches receive constant voltage (one high and the other low), and the lateral piezo voltage is then adjusted to an intermediate value, under continuous feedback control, to obtain the desired final position.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] The non-powered behaviour of this piezoelectric motor is one of two options: *normally locked* or *normally free*.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] A normally free type allows free movement when unpowered but can still be locked by applying a voltage.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] The inchworm motor is commonly used in scanning tunneling microscopes (STMs).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] An STM requires nanometer-scale control of its scanning tip near the material it is observing.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] This control can be accomplished by connecting the scanning tip to the shaft of the inchworm motor.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] The inchworm motor in turn allows control in a direction normal to the plane of the observed material's surface.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Movement across the surface is commonly referred to as movement in the x-y plane, whereas movement normal to the surface is commonly referred to as movement in the z-direction.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] Movement of the scanning tip by the inchworm motor is either manually controlled or automatically controlled by connecting the motor to a feedback system.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] The inchworm motor can be used in patch clamping of biological cells.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] This technique is most often performed with an optical microscope and a micromanipulator holding a glass pipette.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/inchworm-motor] The inchworm motor is particularly ideal in patch clamping because it provides the operator with virtually an instantaneous, precise, smooth and predictable motion without drift.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] A **piezoelectric motor** or **piezo motor** is a type of electric motor based on the change in shape of a piezoelectric material when an electric field is applied, as a consequence of the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] An electrical circuit makes acoustic or ultrasonic vibrations in the piezoelectric material, most often lead zirconate titanate and occasionally lithium niobate or other single-crystal materials, which can produce linear or rotary motion depending on their mechanism.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Examples of types of piezoelectric motors include inchworm motors, stepper and slip-stick motors as well as ultrasonic motors which can be further categorized into standing wave and travelling wave motors.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The growth and forming of piezoelectric crystals is a well-developed industry, yielding very uniform and consistent distortion for a given applied potential difference.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] This, combined with the minute scale of the distortions, gives the piezoelectric motor the ability to make very fine steps.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Manufacturers claim precision to the nanometer scale.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] High response rate and fast distortion of the crystals also let the steps happen at very high frequencies—upwards of 5 MHz.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] This provides a maximum linear speed of approximately 800 mm per second, or nearly 2.9 km/h.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] A unique capability of piezoelectric motors is their ability to operate in strong magnetic fields.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] This extends their usefulness to applications that cannot use traditional electromagnetic motors—such as inside nuclear magnetic resonance antennas.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The maximum operating temperature is limited by the Curie temperature of the used piezoelectric ceramic and can exceed +250 °C.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The main benefits of piezoelectric motors are the high positioning precision, stability of position while unpowered, and the ability to be fabricated at very small sizes or in unusual shapes such as thin rings.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Common applications of piezoelectric motors include focusing systems in camera lenses as well as precision motion control in specialised applications such as microscopy.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Ultrasonic motors differ from other piezoelectric motors in several ways, though both typically use some form of piezoelectric material.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The most obvious difference is the use of resonance to amplify the vibration of the stator in contact with the rotor in ultrasonic motors.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Two different ways are generally available to control the friction along the stator-rotor contact interface, traveling-wave vibration and standing-wave vibration.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Some of the earliest versions of practical motors in the 1970s, by Sashida, for example, used standing-wave vibration in combination with fins placed at an angle to the contact surface to form a motor, albeit one that rotated in a single direction.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Later designs by Sashida and researchers at Matsushita, ALPS, Xeryon and Canon made use of traveling-wave vibration to obtain bi-directional motion, and found that this arrangement offered better efficiency and less contact interface wear.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The inchworm motor uses piezoelectric ceramics to push a stator using a walking-type motion.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] These piezoelectric motors use three groups of crystals—two 'locking', and one 'motive' that permanently connects to either the motor's casing or stator (not both).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The motive group, sandwiched between the other two, provides the motion.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The non-powered behaviour of this piezoelectric motor is one of two options: 'normally locked' or 'normally free'.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Inchworm motors can achieve nanometre-scale positioning by varying the voltage applied to the motive crystal while one set of locking crystals is engaged.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Next, the 'motive' crystal group is triggered and held.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The expansion of this group moves the unlocked 'locking' group along the motor path.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] This is the only stage where the motor moves.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Then the 'locking' group triggered in stage one releases (in 'normally locking' motors, in the other it triggers).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Then the 'motive' group releases, retracting the 'trailing locking' group.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Finally, both 'locking' groups return to their default states.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Not to be confused with the similarly named electromagnetic stepper motor, these motors are similar to the inchworm motor, however, the piezoelectric elements can be bimorph actuators which bend to feed the slider rather than using a separate expanding and contracting element.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The mechanism of slip-stick motors rely on the inertia in combination with the difference between static and dynamic friction.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The stepping action consists of a slow extension phase where static friction is not overcome, followed by a rapid contraction phase where static friction is overcome and the point of contact between the motor and moving part is changed.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The direct drive piezoelectric motor creates movement through continuous ultrasonic vibration.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Its control circuit applies a two-channel sinusoidal or square wave to the piezoelectric elements that matches the bending resonant frequency of the threaded tube—typically an ultrasonic frequency of 40 kHz to 200 kHz.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] This creates orbital motion that drives the screw.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] A second drive type, the squiggle motor, uses piezoelectric elements bonded orthogonally to a nut.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Their ultrasonic vibrations rotate a central lead screw.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Very simple single-action stepping motors can be made with piezoelectric crystals.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] For example, with a hard and rigid rotor-spindle coated with a thin layer of a softer material (like a polyurethane rubber), a series of angled piezoelectric transducers can be arranged.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] When the control circuit triggers one group of transducers, they push the rotor one step.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] This design cannot make steps as small or precise as more complex designs, but can reach higher speeds and is cheaper to manufacture.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The first U.S. patent to disclose a vibrationally-driven motor may be "Method and Apparatus for Delivering Vibratory Energy" (U.S.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] The Maropis patent describes a "vibratory apparatus wherein longitudinal vibrations in a resonant coupling element are converted to torsional vibrations in a toroid type resonant terminal element." The first practical piezomotors were designed and produced by V.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-motor] Lavrinenko in Piezoelectronic Laboratory, starting 1964, Kyiv Polytechnic Institute, USSR.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] A **piezoelectric sensor** is a device that uses the piezoelectric effect to measure changes in pressure, acceleration, temperature, strain, or force by converting them to an electrical charge.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The prefix *piezo-* is Greek for 'press' or 'squeeze'.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Piezoelectric sensors are versatile tools for the measurement of various processes.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] They are used for quality assurance, process control, and for research and development in many industries.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Jacques and Pierre Curie discovered the piezoelectric effect in 1880, but only in the 1950s did manufacturers begin to use the piezoelectric effect in industrial sensing applications.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Since then, this measuring principle has been increasingly used, and has become a mature technology with excellent inherent reliability.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] They have been successfully used in various applications, such as in medical, aerospace, nuclear instrumentation, and as a tilt sensor in consumer electronics or a pressure sensor in the touch pads of mobile phones.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] In the automotive industry, piezoelectric elements are used to monitor combustion when developing internal combustion engines.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The sensors are either directly mounted into additional holes into the cylinder head or the spark/glow plug is equipped with a built-in miniature piezoelectric sensor.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The rise of piezoelectric technology is directly related to a set of inherent advantages.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The high modulus of elasticity of many piezoelectric materials is comparable to that of many metals and goes up to 106 N/m2.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Even though piezoelectric sensors are electromechanical systems that react to compression, the sensing elements show almost zero deflection.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] This gives piezoelectric sensors ruggedness, an extremely high natural frequency and an excellent linearity over a wide amplitude range.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Additionally, piezoelectric technology is insensitive to electromagnetic fields and radiation, enabling measurements under harsh conditions.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Some materials used (especially gallium phosphate or tourmaline) are extremely stable at high temperatures, enabling sensors to have a working range of up to 1000 °C.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Tourmaline shows pyroelectricity in addition to the piezoelectric effect; this is the ability to generate an electrical signal when the temperature of the crystal changes.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] This effect is also common to piezoceramic materials.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] One disadvantage of piezoelectric sensors is that they cannot be used for truly static measurements.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] A static force results in a fixed amount of charge on the piezoelectric material.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] In conventional readout electronics, imperfect insulating materials and reduction in internal sensor resistance causes a constant loss of electrons and yields a decreasing signal.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Elevated temperatures cause an additional drop in internal resistance and sensitivity.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The main effect on the piezoelectric effect is that with increasing pressure loads and temperature, the sensitivity reduces due to twin formation.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] While quartz sensors must be cooled during measurements at temperatures above 300 °C, special types of crystals like GaPO4 gallium phosphate show no twin formation up to the melting point of the material itself.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] However, it is not true that piezoelectric sensors can only be used for very fast processes or at ambient conditions.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] In fact, numerous piezoelectric applications produce quasi-static measurements, and other applications work in temperatures higher than 500 °C.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Piezoelectric sensors can also be used to determine aromas in the air by simultaneously measuring resonance and capacitance.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Computer controlled electronics vastly increase the range of potential applications for piezoelectric sensors.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Piezoelectric sensors are also seen in nature.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The collagen in bone is piezoelectric, and is thought by some to act as a biological force sensor.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Piezoelectricity has also been shown in the collagen of soft tissue such as the Achilles tendon, aortic walls, and heart valves.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] They were also present on BlackBerry’s BlackBerry Storm2, functioning as part of the SurePress technology.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] A force applied along a neutral axis (y) displaces charges along the (x) direction, perpendicular to the line of force.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The amount of charge ( $Q_{x}$ ) depends on the geometrical dimensions of the respective piezoelectric element.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] is the corresponding piezoelectric coefficient.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The amount of charge displaced is strictly proportional to the applied force and independent of the piezoelectric element size and shape.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Putting several elements mechanically in series and electrically in parallel is the only way to increase the charge output.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] corresponds to the number of stacked elements.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The charge produced is exactly proportional to the applied force and is generated at a right angle to the force.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The charge is independent of the element size and shape.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] In contrast to the longitudinal and shear effects, the transverse effect make it possible to fine-tune sensitivity on the applied force and element dimension.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] A piezoelectric transducer can be modeled as a voltage source with a filter.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The voltage *V* at the source is directly proportional to the applied force, pressure, or strain.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The output signal is related to this mechanical force as if it had passed through the filter, which gives the transducer a very high and frequency-dependent output impedance, which results in a frequency response similar to Figure 1.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Figure 2's detailed model includes the effects of the sensor's mechanical construction and other non-idealities.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The inductance *L*m is due to the seismic mass and inertia of the sensor itself.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] *C*e is inversely proportional to the mechanical elasticity of the sensor.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] *C*0 represents the static capacitance of the transducer, resulting from an inertial mass of infinite size.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] These inductances and capacitances are not real electrical elements of the transducer, but rather act as a mechanical–electrical analogy.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Piezo sensors typically use the flat region of the frequency response (the "usable region" in Figure 1) between the high-pass cutoff and the resonant peak.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The load and leakage resistance must be large enough that low frequencies of interest are not lost.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] A simplified equivalent circuit model (top of Figure 3) can be used in this region, in which *C*s represents the capacitance of the sensor surface itself, determined by the standard formula for capacitance of parallel plates.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] This simplified model's Norton equivalent (bottom of Figure 3) is a charge source in parallel with the source capacitance, with the charge directly proportional to the applied force.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Piezoelectric technology can measure various physical quantities, most commonly pressure and acceleration.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] For pressure sensors, a thin membrane and a massive base is used, ensuring that an applied pressure specifically loads the elements in one direction.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] For accelerometers, a seismic mass is attached to the crystal elements.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] When the accelerometer experiences a motion, the invariant seismic mass loads the elements according to Newton's second law of motion $F=ma$ .
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The main difference in working principle between these two cases is the way they apply forces to the sensing elements.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] In a pressure sensor, a thin membrane transfers the force to the elements, while in accelerometers an attached seismic mass applies the forces.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Sensors often tend to be sensitive to more than one physical quantity.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Pressure sensors show false signal when they are exposed to vibrations.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Sophisticated pressure sensors therefore use acceleration compensation elements in addition to the pressure sensing elements.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] By carefully matching those elements, the acceleration signal (released from the compensation element) is subtracted from the combined signal of pressure and acceleration to derive the true pressure information.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Vibration sensors can also harvest otherwise wasted energy from mechanical vibrations.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] This is accomplished by using piezoelectric materials to convert mechanical strain into usable electrical energy.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Three main groups of materials are used for piezoelectric sensors: piezoelectric ceramics, single crystal materials and thin film piezoelectric materials.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The ceramic materials (such as PZT ceramic) have a piezoelectric constant/sensitivity that is roughly two orders of magnitude higher than those of the natural single crystal materials and can be produced by inexpensive sintering processes.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The piezoeffect in piezoceramics is "trained", so their high sensitivity degrades over time.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] This degradation is highly correlated with increased temperature.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The less-sensitive, natural, single-crystal materials (gallium phosphate, quartz, tourmaline) have a higher – when carefully handled, almost unlimited – long term stability.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] There are also new single-crystal materials commercially available such as Lead Magnesium Niobate-Lead Titanate (PMN-PT).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] These materials offer improved sensitivity over PZT but have a lower maximum operating temperature and are currently more complicated to manufacture due to four compound vs. three compound material PZT.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Thin film piezoelectric materials can be manufactured utilizing sputtering, CVD (chemical vapour deposition), ALD (atomic layer epitaxy) etc. methods.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Thin film piezoelectric materials are used in applications where high frequency (> 100 MHz) is utilised in the measurement method and/or small size is favored in the application.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] Self-sensing materials with an aluminum matrix and embedded piezoelectric phases, such as PZT (lead zirconate titanate) or barium titanate, can be produced through Friction Stir Processing (FSP).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] In this process, the piezoelectric particles are dispersed into the aluminum matrix, creating a composite material capable of both structural and sensing functions.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] The piezoelectric particles generate an electrical signal in response to mechanical stress or strain, enabling the material to monitor its own condition.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/piezoelectric-sensor] FSP ensures a fine dispersion of the piezoelectric phase and enhances the bonding between particles and the matrix, leading to improved mechanical and sensing properties.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] An **ultrasonic motor** is a type of piezoelectric motor powered by the ultrasonic vibration of a component, the stator, placed against another component, the rotor or slider depending on the scheme of operation (rotation or linear translation).
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Ultrasonic motors differ from other piezoelectric motors in several ways, though both typically use some form of piezoelectric material, most often lead zirconate titanate and occasionally lithium niobate or other single-crystal materials.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Ultrasonic motors also offer arbitrarily large rotation or sliding distances, while piezoelectric actuators are limited by the static strain that may be induced in the piezoelectric element.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] One common application of ultrasonic motors is in camera lenses where they are used to move lens elements as part of the auto-focus system.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Ultrasonic motors replace the noisier and often slower micro-motor in this application.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Dry friction is often used in contact, and the ultrasonic vibration induced in the stator is used both to impart motion to the rotor and to modulate the frictional forces present at the interface.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] The friction modulation allows bulk motion of the rotor (i.e., for farther than one vibration cycle); without this modulation, ultrasonic motors would fail to operate.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Some of the earliest versions of practical motors in the 1970s, by Sashida, for example, used standing-wave vibration in combination with fins placed at an angle to the contact surface to form a motor, although one that rotated in a single direction.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Later designs by Sashida and researchers at Matsushita, ALPS, and Canon made use of traveling-wave vibration to obtain bi-directional motion, and found that this arrangement offered better efficiency and less contact interface wear.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] A key observation in the study of ultrasonic motors is that the peak vibration that may be induced in structures occurs at a relatively constant *vibration velocity* regardless of frequency.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] The vibration velocity is simply the time derivative of the vibration displacement in a structure, and is not (directly) related to the speed of the wave propagation within a structure.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Many engineering materials suitable for vibration permit a peak vibration velocity of around 1 m/s.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] At low frequencies — 50 Hz, say — a vibration velocity of 1 m/s in a woofer would give displacements of about 10 mm, which is visible.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] As the frequency is increased, the displacement decreases, and the acceleration increases.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] As the vibration becomes inaudible at 20 kHz or so, the vibration displacements are in the tens of micrometers, and motors have been built that operate using 50 MHz surface acoustic wave (SAW) that have vibrations of only a few nanometers in magnitude.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Such devices require care in construction to meet the necessary precision to make use of these motions within the stator.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] More generally, there are two types of motors, contact and non-contact, the latter of which is rare and requires a working fluid to transmit the ultrasonic vibrations of the stator toward the rotor.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Most versions use air, such as some of the earliest versions by Hu Junhui.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Research in this area continues, particularly in near-field acoustic levitation for this sort of application.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Canon was one of the pioneers of the ultrasonic motor, and made the "USM" famous in the late 1980s by incorporating it into its autofocus lenses for the Canon EF lens mount.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Numerous patents on ultrasonic motors have been filed by Canon, its chief lensmaking rival Nikon, and other industrial concerns since the early 1980s.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] Canon has not only included an ultrasonic motor (USM) in their DSLR lenses, but also in the Canon PowerShot SX1 IS bridge camera.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] The ultrasonic motor is now used in many consumer and office electronics requiring precision rotations over long periods of time.
[src:piezoelectric-actuators/ultrasonic-motor] The technology has been applied to photographic lenses by a variety of companies under different names.
